product_name: Dave's Original Insanity Hot Sauce - 5oz
review_body: I enjoy things spicier than most.  This is indeed HOT, but eating it neat doesn't feel quite as intense as eating a fresh habanero to me- my ears were not burning.  The heat is quick to start, strong, and tingly, lasting for several minutes.  The flavor of the sauce reminds me a little of tomato paste with cherries (but not sweet) and I don't really taste chili peppers.  Excellent for kicking things up without altering flavor too much.  A staple in the hot sauce arsenal for intermediate-level hot heads.

product_name: Dave's Original Insanity Hot Sauce - 5oz
review_body: It's pretty spicy. I pour this on my roast beef sandwiches to give them a little kick. I'm well adjusted to spices now in college age, curry is all I eat. So this isn't as INSANITY as it used to be for me. Ahh, teenager me got obliterated when he first tried this.Taste: 4/5Spiciness: 4.5/5Pleasant taste. Mix a couple drops in salsa, chili, soups, etc and it will liven it up. Batches do vary from what I've noticed, some are spicier or more favorable. It's spice level is up there. This is a good entry level to the kingdom of HOT sauce. Make sure to work your way up. If Sriracha and Tabasco is all you've ever tried, you're going to get rekt.

review_body: Wow this sauce is very very very spicy. It's a lingering spice that increases over time. My first time venturing into the high scollies and I'd say this is a good starting point if you're looking to venture into the reaper and Carolina spice level. My only real complaint is the taste of it. It has a strong herb taste that completely changes the flavor profile of whatever you're adding it into. And it can almost dominate the original flavor. So all you can really taste is just the herby hot sauce and your mouth on fire. I like my spices to add only spice and maybe enhance the flavor, not something that completely takes over the flavor profile.  And there is no regulator or drip so be careful when you pour cause a lot can come out, and you'll be tempted to not waste it... Just let it go...

product_name: Mad Dog 357 Hot Sauce, 5 Ounce
review_title: good bbq flavor for use in pot of chili or ...
review_body: I've got a story to go along with this sauce but first the pro's and cons.Pros: Very hot, good bbq flavor for use in pot of chili or wings.cons: limited flavor use, delayed heat spike.After ordering this product, I sampled the sauce with a small toothpick drop.  The taste leans more towards a strong smokey flavor rather than the expected "chili" flavor.  The heat of this product hits you about 3 minutes after ingestion so there's quite the delay in spiciness.  After sampling a small amount, and gaining the courage to try one solid drop, I accidentally dropped 3 nickel-sized drops on a chip.  Thinking I could move past it easily I went ahead and ate the chip.  Fast forward 10 minutes and I was bent over the porcelain throne, while my girlfriend was calling an ambulance.  I blacked out and came to, with two paramedics kneeling over me performing the necessary procedures to stabilize me.  I temporarily lost the vision in my right eye for about 15 minutes until the medicine they gave me revived my vision.  I showed them the product and they informed me that ingesting spicy sauces like this one can cause permanent damage to organs and shut them down temporarily as was the case in my situation.  1 star for this product because it definitely delivered on heat but is definitely a health hazard and "at-your-own-risk" as it says on the bottle.

I was surprised at how much give the tent had at 17 mph gusts and did not break any poles or tear. It bounced right back to itâ€™s original form.Conâ€™s:1). review_title: Sand, mud, wind, t-storms, flooding, hail, rain by the bucket. Tent tested and approved by a camping pro video proof.
review_body: Â We are huge amazon shoppers for many years and never wrote a review. With this product We decided to do a review months after we used it. We went on a 10 day camping trip through northern Michigan with our 2 and 4 year olds. This was our first trip for the kids and the wife. I actually teach outdoor education, survival skills, team building, and everything that comes with it for over 15 years and countless experience prior. All I need in the woods is about 5 items and I would do just fine for quite some time. My wife and kids on the other hand need much, much, much more. So we planned this trip pretty hard core and invested in a ton of things that most would not -the main thing was a portable potty and a tent for that- and of course a tent. We picked this tent after searching and searching for what would work best for our family.We traveled from spot to spot only spending a few days at a time in locations and covered some miles. This tent saw the dunes, rugged campsites, perfect campsite, grass, sand, dirt, mud, rain, thunderstorms, flooding, you name it. It held strong. The kids were happy and most important the wife was happy. This was her very first camping trip and she loved it. This is something i was worried about and i went to great lengths to make this a perfect trip so we can do this over and over again. Camping is a dying art and i grew up camping and in my mind mastered it. So it was a win for our family and me.We waterproofed this tent with a spray. We made sure the fly was perfect and this thing was staked down properly each time. This is very very important. It takes time to get that right with a new tent but history has taught me a ton. I have read reviews and most of the bad ones i can tell you right now are people that had no clue what they were doing and did not put in the time to master the most important tool of a camping trip. The tent. We spent hours mastering this tent before we even hit the road. HOURS. When you pull up to set up you best have a plan and know your tent. If you dont then im sure you will take it out by writing a bad review and making guys like me laugh. Thanks for that. Put in the time.I am attaching a video of our biggest challenge on our massive adventure. We were in the middle of nowhere on our 6th day when the mother of all thunderstorms and flood maker arrived at our campsite. It kinda takes a lot for me to worry in any situation. I worried for about 2 min and knew we were good. Being confident in your tent when you are hours from a hotel is a great feeling. I can say this about this tent. My wife and kids hearts were pounding and they were straight up scared while I was loving the thrill. Once everyone knew we were not going to float away and our tent was water tight it turned out to be pretty fun and a heart pounding memory we all will keep forever. Put in the time, dont let camping become a dying art, and oh ya....PUT IN THE TIME. Your wife will thank you later....

review_title: Sand, mud, wind, t-storms, flooding, hail, rain by the bucket. Tent tested and approved by a camping pro video proof.
review_body: Â We are huge amazon shoppers for many years and never wrote a review. With this product We decided to do a review months after we used it. We went on a 10 day camping trip through northern Michigan with our 2 and 4 year olds. This was our first trip for the kids and the wife. I actually teach outdoor education, survival skills, team building, and everything that comes with it for over 15 years and countless experience prior. All I need in the woods is about 5 items and I would do just fine for quite some time. My wife and kids on the other hand need much, much, much more. So we planned this trip pretty hard core and invested in a ton of things that most would not -the main thing was a portable potty and a tent for that- and of course a tent. We picked this tent after searching and searching for what would work best for our family.We traveled from spot to spot only spending a few days at a time in locations and covered some miles. This tent saw the dunes, rugged campsites, perfect campsite, grass, sand, dirt, mud, rain, thunderstorms, flooding, you name it. It held strong. The kids were happy and most important the wife was happy. This was her very first camping trip and she loved it. This is something i was worried about and i went to great lengths to make this a perfect trip so we can do this over and over again. Camping is a dying art and i grew up camping and in my mind mastered it. So it was a win for our family and me.We waterproofed this tent with a spray. We made sure the fly was perfect and this thing was staked down properly each time. This is very very important. It takes time to get that right with a new tent but history has taught me a ton. I have read reviews and most of the bad ones i can tell you right now are people that had no clue what they were doing and did not put in the time to master the most important tool of a camping trip. The tent. We spent hours mastering this tent before we even hit the road. HOURS. When you pull up to set up you best have a plan and know your tent. If you dont then im sure you will take it out by writing a bad review and making guys like me laugh. Thanks for that. Put in the time.I am attaching a video of our biggest challenge on our massive adventure. We were in the middle of nowhere on our 6th day when the mother of all thunderstorms and flood maker arrived at our campsite. It kinda takes a lot for me to worry in any situation. I worried for about 2 min and knew we were good. Being confident in your tent when you are hours from a hotel is a great feeling. I can say this about this tent. My wife and kids hearts were pounding and they were straight up scared while I was loving the thrill. Once everyone knew we were not going to float away and our tent was water tight it turned out to be pretty fun and a heart pounding memory we all will keep forever. Put in the time, dont let camping become a dying art, and oh ya....PUT IN THE TIME. Your wife will thank you later....

Wenzel Klondike Tent - 8 Person

product_name: Dave's Original Insanity Hot Sauce - 5oz
review_title: Exactly what it says on the package - Insanity
review_body: Extremely hot! This sauce is no joke. My dad tried a spoonful of it while he was working up in Alaska. Big mistake. He couldn't breathe. It nearly sent him to the hospital. I was smart enough to put some on a spoon and then dip the tip of my tongue into it, not try and eat a whole spoonful. This sauce is extremely thick and concentrated. It barely runs out of the bottle without some shaking for encouragement. It has a very bitter pepper extract flavor up-front, with a touch of smoky habanero. If you can get over the nasty bitterness, you might even be encouraged to try some more. Don't. Then, the burn hits. After tasting just a little of this, you will need milk. Like, five glasses of milk. And it's oily and the milk just spreads it around your mouth and makes the burn worse, at first. If you like spicing up your food, this is very economical; a teaspoon will make any dish almost inedibly hot for most people. One bottle will last a very, very long time. Don't be dismayed by the gross flavor; when diluted in a bowl of chili con carne, the bitterness vanishes.

product_name: Dave's Original Insanity Hot Sauce - 5oz
review_body: This is pretty hot, but the extract in it tastes like a well behaved pepperspray or O.C. As we call it in the law enforcement community. I have been pepper sprayed as part of my police training and found that this sauce has a very similar flavor to that Sabre Red. Its like a strong dried red cayenne pepper flavor. To conclude, i will say that this sauce is not for a beginner or average consumer, i call it "medium" heat, but I'm a chili head and like that kind of pain.

product_name: Dave's Original Insanity Hot Sauce - 5oz
review_body: Hot, but I don't care for the flavor.  Although a friend of mine loves it and recommended it to me but I'm more into flavorful eat than pure burn.

product_name: Dave's Original Insanity Hot Sauce - 5oz
review_body: I enjoy things spicier than most.  This is indeed HOT, but eating it neat doesn't feel quite as intense as eating a fresh habanero to me- my ears were not burning.  The heat is quick to start, strong, and tingly, lasting for several minutes.  The flavor of the sauce reminds me a little of tomato paste with cherries (but not sweet) and I don't really taste chili peppers.  Excellent for kicking things up without altering flavor too much.  A staple in the hot sauce arsenal for intermediate-level hot heads.

product_name: Dave's Original Insanity Hot Sauce - 5oz
review_body: It's pretty spicy. I pour this on my roast beef sandwiches to give them a little kick. I'm well adjusted to spices now in college age, curry is all I eat. So this isn't as INSANITY as it used to be for me. Ahh, teenager me got obliterated when he first tried this.Taste: 4/5Spiciness: 4.5/5Pleasant taste. Mix a couple drops in salsa, chili, soups, etc and it will liven it up. Batches do vary from what I've noticed, some are spicier or more favorable. It's spice level is up there. This is a good entry level to the kingdom of HOT sauce. Make sure to work your way up. If Sriracha and Tabasco is all you've ever tried, you're going to get rekt.

review_title: Tastes Like a Pile of Burning Tire-Rubber, but it's a Classic
review_body: When I was a kid, I have some seriously traumatic memories of this stuff ruining my day on a couple occasions. In fact until recently I only used this stuff as an additive to heat up other more flavorful sauces. Now that there are lots of sauces that are both several-times hotter and have much better flavor, I doubt I'll be revisiting this sauce any time soon. I'll give Dave's Original Insanity a tip of the hat for being a classic that really introduced me to the soul-searing heat of extract sauces. But in the current world with tons and tons of other options, do your research before settling for this sauce.

product_name: Mad Dog 357 Hot Sauce, 5 Ounce
review_body: Wow this sauce is very very very spicy. It's a lingering spice that increases over time. My first time venturing into the high scollies and I'd say this is a good starting point if you're looking to venture into the reaper and Carolina spice level. My only real complaint is the taste of it. It has a strong herb taste that completely changes the flavor profile of whatever you're adding it into. And it can almost dominate the original flavor. So all you can really taste is just the herby hot sauce and your mouth on fire. I like my spices to add only spice and maybe enhance the flavor, not something that completely takes over the flavor profile.  And there is no regulator or drip so be careful when you pour cause a lot can come out, and you'll be tempted to not waste it... Just let it go...

product_name: Mad Dog 357 Hot Sauce, 5 Ounce
review_title: good bbq flavor for use in pot of chili or ...
review_body: I've got a story to go along with this sauce but first the pro's and cons.Pros: Very hot, good bbq flavor for use in pot of chili or wings.cons: limited flavor use, delayed heat spike.After ordering this product, I sampled the sauce with a small toothpick drop.  The taste leans more towards a strong smokey flavor rather than the expected "chili" flavor.  The heat of this product hits you about 3 minutes after ingestion so there's quite the delay in spiciness.  After sampling a small amount, and gaining the courage to try one solid drop, I accidentally dropped 3 nickel-sized drops on a chip.  Thinking I could move past it easily I went ahead and ate the chip.  Fast forward 10 minutes and I was bent over the porcelain throne, while my girlfriend was calling an ambulance.  I blacked out and came to, with two paramedics kneeling over me performing the necessary procedures to stabilize me.  I temporarily lost the vision in my right eye for about 15 minutes until the medicine they gave me revived my vision.  I showed them the product and they informed me that ingesting spicy sauces like this one can cause permanent damage to organs and shut them down temporarily as was the case in my situation.  1 star for this product because it definitely delivered on heat but is definitely a health hazard and "at-your-own-risk" as it says on the bottle.

product_name: Secret Aardvark Habanero Sauce, Net 8 fl oz.
review_title: A versatile sauce, too subtle and too costly to be a regular buy.
review_body: This sauce has a medium heat level (for hot sauces) and great balance of flavors for a sweeter sauce. As it is tomato based, it is more similar to the "Mexican Ketchups" I've had in Europe then a traditional vinegar or chili forward hot sauce. The flavors are subtle or muddied (depending on your disposition) which allows it to accompany a wider variety of foods without being overpowering. However, that also means it lacks a bit of the punch and perk of more straight forward sauces.For my own taste this sauce is a bit too indistinct. While it goes well with just about everything, it doesn't lend itself to particular pairings the way that less complicated sauces do. However, if you are the kind of person that likes sriracha and is looking for the next sauce to put on everything, this is a fine offering.

review_title: I am very disappointed. I expected a $120 pair of shoes to ...

review_body: And still reacting. It's not that they aren't gluten free. It's that your body sees the protein in oats as the same protein as gluten because they are very similar in structure. I can't eat oats, my 5 year old can't eat oats, my 8 year old old gets sick from eating certified GF oatmeal but not cereal with oat flour. So, it's not necessarily Cheerios making a false statement or not doing their due diligence,  it's your body can't tolerate oats. The allergist who diagnosed me also had celiac and was the same way. We commiserated over our love of oatmeal cookies.

product_name: Honey Nut Cheerios Gluten Free Breakfast Cereal, 26.6 oz, Giant Size Cereal Box
review_body: And still reacting. It's not that they aren't gluten free. It's that your body sees the protein in oats as the same protein as gluten because they are very similar in structure. I can't eat oats, my 5 year old can't eat oats, my 8 year old old gets sick from eating certified GF oatmeal but not cereal with oat flour. So, it's not necessarily Cheerios making a false statement or not doing their due diligence,  it's your body can't tolerate oats. The allergist who diagnosed me also had celiac and was the same way. We commiserated over our love of oatmeal cookies.

review_body: Tried for hours to clone 1 drive of a 2 drive system to get to boot on a PC.  No luck.  Fresh installing Win10 from USB drive was the key.  On a Mac, you can clone the singular drive and it was plug and play (maybe cloning from a 1 drive system is easier).  What a relief!  How fast is the drive?  With an i7 desktop coming from 2x5400 rpm drives to 1 SSD was 45 seconds to 7 seconds.  By the time I turn on the monitor I am already in the login screen. Programs load within 1-3 seconds.  3 seconds for video editors.  I will buy another SSD to separate programs from the Win drive.  Another bonus- No noise.  My Shuttle mini desktop now has only a few pulses of videofan noise and a very low drone of power supply noise.  The whole computer is practically silent.  This SSD has literally saved minutes every day and power, too.  When I leave the room, I used to leave the computer on and return half an hour later, but now I just turn it off- it literally only takes seconds to turn on.

review_body: Its absolutely wonderful for the price and the kids love it. It does stink from time to time so you'll need to clean it more often than others, but I've had it a while now and it still works pretty good. My only other complaint is the temperature doesn't work right. product_name: Star Wars Millennium Falcon Waffle Maker
review_title: Used Alton Brown's buttermilk waffle recipe from Good Eats Vol 2 (the book)
review_body: Used Alton Brown's buttermilk waffle recipe from Good Eats Vol 2 (the book).I got three novelty waffle makers this last Christmas.  This one is better than the Death Star waffle maker: You get much more even browning (but not in the center well where the Rebel symbol is).The waffles this iron makes do have a cross-sectional thickness that seems to be about the same as models of the ship.  This results in some uneven browning, but I can live with that.If you want the front sponsons and the cockpit to come out right in the finished waffle, you do have to make sure you get some batter in those areas.  Which can be tricky with thick waffle batter.  Still, you'll get some expansion of the batter as the leavening kicks in, but it doesn't seem to fill these areas if there isn't any batter in them.Only thing I'd suggest changing about this iron is to not make that center hole quite so deep.

product_name: Remington Impact Resistant Hair Dryer, D4200
review_title: The Best Dryer I've Ever Used
review_body: This is by far the best hair dryer I have ever owned.  I have used it for several months now as I wanted to see how it held up over time.  I wash and dry my hair daily.  I have shoulder length, very thick hair.  I have never had a hair dryer dry my hair as fast as this one.  I use a dryer until my hair is almost dry and let the air finish.  I only have to use this dryer for about 5-minutes to achieve what in the past would take 10 minutes or longer.I've used the dryer every day for almost 4 months.  It works just as well as it did on day one.It's powerful but not heavy.The dryer is between 11 to 12 inches tall.  The handle is 7-inches long; longer than I was used to but it was easy to adapt.  I like the longer handle but had to get used to the location of the flip-switch controls.  It was easy for my fingers to change the setting without me realizing it until I got used to them.The cord is 60-inches (5-feet) not including the GFCI-plug.I use a wall mount hair dryer holder but this dryer has an attached plastic ring on the back of the handle to hang the dryer if needed.The chrome coated parts of the dryer have not flaked, chipped or peeled anywhere.  The chrome and black color matches my cream and black bathroom but would look good with just about any color combinations.This is my favorite hair dryer and I plan on purchasing a spare for when this one quits.Made In China

product_name: Remington Impact Resistant Hair Dryer, D4200
review_title: Buttons in Bad Place, But Nice Hair Dryer
review_body: For the most part, this hair dryer is better than its price would suggest.  It feels solid and puts out a nice flow of air.  There is plenty of heat, but also an option for lukewarm air.  I love that low heat option, which means I don't need to hold down a button for drying without heat.  The attachments are also nice.  The only downside is that the buttons are easy to accidentally hit while I am moving the hair dryer around my head.  They sit on grip handle, which is just not the best place to have them when they are the type that toggle without much force.  Still, other than this quirk, I think it is a good choice for the price.

It was pancake thin no matter how much batter I used.

product_name: Star Wars Death Star Waffle Maker
review_body: It's not a waffle, it more like a pancake.

product_name: Star Wars Death Star Waffle Maker
review_title: The Death Star has a major flaw, and so does this waffle maker.
review_body: Maybe the worst waffle maker ever.  Perhaps ours was defective, but it took 20 minutes to get hot, and then the batter cooled off the iron, so it took another 15 minutes to make a Star Wars pancake, and a flimsy one at that.  Honestly, there is not enough depth to the iron to really make a waffle.

product_name: Star Wars Death Star Waffle Maker
review_title: and they came out super flat and pancake-like
review_body: Did not cook waffles fully, and they came out super flat and pancake-like. Do not recommend.

product_name: Star Wars Death Star Waffle Maker
review_title: Cool item, could use a few adjustments and would be great!
review_body: Using Alton Brown's buttermilk waffle recipe from Good Eats Vol 2 (the book) -I really like the concept.  Here are the issues I have with this product, your mileage may vary:1: The plates are too large.  The resulting waffles will not fit in a standard toaster for reheating.  If the plates were reduced in diameter by about an inch, that would be perfect.2: The lands and grooves do not have enough separation - this reduces the cooking surface area and prevents the waffles from crisping up in the iron, even with the heat control set at max.Those are the two problems with it that need fixing.  If they fix them, they could also make the total distance between the low points on both the upper and lower plates a touch further from each other.With those two adjustments, I'd probably give this unit a five star review.

product_name: Star Wars Death Star Waffle Maker
review_body: Comes out great with perfect design. Only thing that sucks is is takes forever to cook one. Iâ€™m in a family of five and we all finished eating after like an hour. Not really efficient for eating as a family.

product_name: Star Wars Death Star Waffle Maker
review_title: I saw that in the reviews before but I like a smaller pocket
review_body: Mostly a pancake maker... I saw that in the reviews before but I like a smaller pocket, crispier waffle (vs a belgian) so that sounded not to bad to me. But this just does not get crispy on the outside too well. I have only tried one recipe (my favorite family recipe) so maybe I will just have to try some others. Also it does not make a clear signal when the waffle is done. There are lights but they don't seem to function like the manual says they will? I prefer whistle or tone.  I don't normally like to have excess appliances so I wanted this to be my be all end all waffle maker replacement and it is not that. Overall it is a cool novelty and we will get enjoyment out of it.

product_name: Star Wars Death Star Waffle Maker
review_title: A problem with the thermal exhaust port
review_body: A curious machine; however, there was a slight problem with the waffles it produced.  A seemingly insignificant thermal exhaust port (right below the main port) was easily exploited by a bead of syrup.  Unfortunately, our waffles were destroyed just outside of Yavin 4.

product_name: Star Wars Death Star Waffle Maker
review_body: While it does make a waffle that has the Death Star imprinted on it, the waffles are incredibly thin.  The coolness factor of this item does not outweigh the fact that this is not a very good waffle iron.Despite the waffles being thin, it takes quite a long time for a waffle to be cooked on it.  It's also VERY easy to put too much batter onto the iron and make a huge mess, with batter that drips down inside the machine.The lid isn't very heavy (despite the description saying it's a weighted lid) and I found I had to put something heavy on top to keep the top plate from rising too much once the waffle (finally) starts to cook.After a few uses, I had to disassemble it to clean the batter out from inside the maker and I wound up breaking some of the plastic molded pieces trying to re-assemble the unit.  A very cheap design and you need to be careful not to put too much batter in this maker.

product_name: Wireless Earbuds, ENACFIRE E18 Bluetooth Earbuds 15H Playtime 3D Stereo Sound Wireless Headphones
review_title: Even the right bud can be paired individually
review_body: Actually I want to start off saying that you are able to use them individually one at a time when one is charging using either the left or right one. Before purchasing these, that was a big concern that never had a definitive answer and every reviewer said they couldn't get it to work. I also had issues with getting this to work originally and I saw all the reviews have stated the same thing that they were only able to use the left one individually but the right one would not work without the left one being on. Out of the box that is the case because the left is default as master and the right is the slave. Meaning that the left one is the one that is connected to your phone and the right ear bud connects to your left ear bud. It took me a couple of tries even after I got the explanation from contacting the seller multiple times to grasp more clarity. What you need to do is turn the right one into a master as well and you do this by turning it on and placing it back in the box and taking it out of the box again and having and holding the power button until you hear it say pairing, once that is accomplished you will see it blinks white/blue and you're able to connect your phone to the ear bud. Also make sure you've unpaired any e18 Bluetooth names before doing this since they use the same Bluetooth name for left and right which makes it a hassle to use them individually but I understand the appeal of doing so.I was skeptical at first about these ear buds doing everything I wanted. The sound quality was not high on my list of things necessary for the ear buds. I don't like to listen to loud music and even working out I only want it at a minimal level that I can set it and not have to strain to hear what I'm listening to or watching.I wanted ear buds that I could use one and my wife could use one but left and right would be connected to our separate devices. I also wanted a device that could be used as a pair when we wanted to watch something together. I also needed to make sure they have some kind of resistance to sweat or light usage near water.I researched and could not find one official waterproof ear bud on the market. I found some that stated water proof but then in the description would say it is an ipx5 which is not close to being waterproof.i wouldn't say they are being fallacious but maybe it's the translation that just went awry.That being said these have held up through my workouts and I sweat like a beast. The audio is clear and the range is very good. The battery has held up well so far and I will update if that changes. I will say if u plan on using both ear buds out of the box they are very easy to setup. Once the right is connected to your phone the left will automatically connect when taken out of the charging box. That being said I would still honestly only pick up another pair if the price drops back down.

product_name: Wireless Earbuds, ENACFIRE E18 Bluetooth Earbuds 15H Playtime 3D Stereo Sound Wireless Headphones
review_title: Excellent earbuds with an excellent price
review_body: I wish that I purchased these a long time ago! I'm an audio file and I love listening to music all of the time. I'm really impressed with their sound and their ability to block out outside noise. I tested the range and they work just fine even when I was over 30 ft. away from them. They're very easy to use and it's easy to accept a phone call through them. The price on these earbuds should have twice as much! I was going to buy the expensive earbuds by Bose for $200 and I'm really glad that I didn't. You won't be disappointed with these!

review_title: Good headphones but don't work outdoors
review_body: Setup was super easy, and when using indoors:1. connectivity is great2. audio quality is very good3. phone call quality is decent tooUnfortunately, the moment you step outside and are close to other people, the connection between the left and right headphones gets messed up. You will hear only from the left, then only from the right and then the audio bitrate changes. This happens almost always when I am close to a group of people. I think the headphones get affected by other Bluetooth signals around. I live in New York and there are people all around so this just doesn't work.I really wish these headphones worked outside as they are great looking and work amazing when I am indoors.

review_title: Not perfect, but they're an unbelievable value!  Everyone should own a pair.
review_body: This is a quick review after having received them earlier today.Amazing product for only $50.  I can't attest to their longevity, but the quality and features at this price are simply amazing even if they end up not lasting forever.  I've wanted a pair with individual wireless buds for over a decade, but haven't found anything comparable in previous years for under $350.Sounds quality could be better; it's not as great as everyone seems to make it out to be in the reviews, but it's still very good and certainly as good as one should expect from a $50 pair of wireless headphones.You can't adjust the volume on them, but you can pause and skip to the next song.  Haven't tested the call quality, but I'm sure it's adequate.Very impressed upon first use.  There could be better or higher quality products, but anyone will be impressed with these for the price.

review_title: Skeptical at first but I am a total believer. Would absolutely recommend.
review_body: This is the perfect earbud for using at work where I want to listen to music without having an extra earbud dangling on a wire in order to keep one ear open to communicate with coworkers. It is also perfect for using when on my motorcycle to listen to music but still wanting to hear engine noise and noise from traffic around me for safety reasons. It is low profile enough to easily go underneath my helmet. Sound is what you would expect for a $15 device but does great even with peripheral noise while out on my bike.This earbud fits comfortably in either ear. It pairs effortlessly with my phone when turned on and the range is shocking. I can walk throughout my apartment even when walls interfere and audio is rarely broken up. The magnetic charger is great as I can slip into the USB on my monitor and load the earbud right to it whenever I leave the office for the day. I can't speak to the advertised battery life but have never had to recharge mid-day while at work.I was extremely puzzled when I first saw these as to why you would sell a single earbud at a time that came with two chargers. I still do not completely understand the double charger offer but I am not going to turn it down. I now have a backup!

product_name: Minimalism Art | Classic Notebook Journal, Size: 5" X 8.3", A5, Yellow, Dotted Grid Page, 192 Pages, Hard Cover/Fine PU Leather, Inner Pocket, Quality Paper - 100gsm | Designed in San Francisco
review_body: This is a great little notebook.With regards to the outside, the cover is perfectly subtle; all black faux-leather with a nearly invisible "Minimalism Art" stamped on the back cover. The elastic band holding the notebook closed is much stronger than I'm used to for notebooks of this cost, and seems like it will hold up for some time.On the inside, the inside cover and first page are un-gridded pages with the Minimalism Art logo and a "Return to if Found" label, respectively. I personally love that the first page isn't a sketch page -- I find that I always hate coming back to whatever my first sketch in the book is every time I open my notes, and this avoids that perfectly.The actual grid pages are a soft beige color with a printed light grey grid in standard size. Thusfar, I've found that these colors work well to let you see the grid when you need to or ignore it when you're not looking for it. I haven't yet tried to scan these pages, so I don't know if this grid color will make scanning difficult but I suspect it won't be the case with a quick visual check.Remarkably, the book is bound well enough that the grid lines match up over the spine *on every page*. I usually resign myself to never letting a sketch spill over the spine, but in this case it can be done. As well, the binding leaves a very shallow crevice between the two pages: if you pull the two pages taut, they almost lay flat with each other. I suspect that holding the pages flat in this way would damage the book if you did it frequently, but for the occasional two-page layout it's very neat.I'm not very deep into this notebook yet, so I can't speak on durability yet -- so far it seems like it will hold up very well. If there is an issue at any point, I'll return to this review and note it.

review_title: I wanted to love this journal and I would if I was not ...
review_body: I wanted to love this journal and I would if I was not a fountain pen writer.Seriously it has all the functions I pay high money for: ribbon page marker, great pen holder, good elastic band for closure, nice padded cover, inside envelope and made in America.Yea!Damn although most people love the thicker paper I don't. I found it is not a good medium for water color doodles and a very clumsy vehicle for fountain pen ink.The paper is thick and coarse for my preferences. Paper like this drags on a fine nib and the result is a slow sluggish pen traversal across the page. Most fp people love Rhodia for Euro paper or Tomoe River for Japanese paper. Both of these are slick not abrasive surfaces that allow a fountain pen to glide across the page. That is the primary reason we write with fountain pens and then seek the perfect paper and feel triply blessed with an outstanding journal.This is an excellent journal by most standards and I would personally shout its praises IF it contained a higher grade of paper.Q.

product_name: Cornell 5/8/77
review_body: This is a good show, no question about it.  I've had this show on cassette and then CD for more than 25 years, and now finally the band was able to regain possession of the original tapes and we have an official release.  This show was released as part of a boxed set that also contained the shows from May 5th, May 7th and May 9th, and it was also given an individual release.  The songs most talked about from this show are the Scarlet > Fire medley, Dancing In The Street, Estimated Prophet, St. Stephen and Morning Dew.  The Scarlet > Fire is in my top two ever, the other being Portland '77.  Dancing In The Street is the 'disco-fied' version they'd been playing since 1976, and I don't understand the attraction; it's just awful.  The Estimated Prophet is one of the all-time best versions, as are many from the early part of 1977.  I also fail to understand the popularity of the post-hiatus versions of St. Stephen, they were uniformly awful after the song was re-commissioned in 1976.  It just wasn't a good fit for that line-up, at that time, with that repertoire.  They put it back on the shelf shortly thereafter and it wasn't heard again until 1983, and after a few airings it was put away for good...and I do mean for good.  Lastly, we have Morning Dew.  It's hard to find a truly bad version of that song, and this isn't one of them.  It's a good vocal performance from Garcia, and the quality of the recording doesn't hurt either.  The reason I brought up these few songs is to point out the fact that there were 13 more songs played at the show and I rarely hear a word about them.  Aside from the fact that the version of Loser may be the very best they ever played, that leaves a whole bunch of other songs that rarely get a mention...and this show is often touted as 'The Best Show They Ever Played'.  It isn't.  If you can get your hands on the Buffalo show from May 9th, get that one; I prefer it over this show every time.  I can't get real excited about a show when roughly 25% of it is acknowledged as 'great' and the rest of it is largely ignored.  The Buffalo show starts out great and maintains a high level of proficiency throughout the entire show, song after song after song.  Get this one for the highlights, there are quite a few.  But get the Buffalo show if you want consistent greatness throughout.

product_name: Cornell 5/8/77
review_title: GD arguably their best live album EVER!
review_body: There is almost nothing negative I can say about this album. Starts off amazing, and once Dancing in the Streets starts, the album goes from amazing to epic. Since decades have past, itâ€™s gone from epic to legendary. GD has so many amazing shows, this one is so pure, the sound is so amazing, and all the vocals are at their best. If your a fan of the GD, or are new to the Dead and are looking to find an album to start your collection, please donâ€™t pass this up. This whole tour was incredible, but this show in particular is nothing short of breathtaking. I cannot stress enough how good this album is. Incredibly psychedelic, some of Jerryâ€™s best guitar playing...everyone in the band is spot on - NOT TO BE MISSED!!!!!

product_name: Cornell 5/8/77
review_title: Awful Sound ... Don't Waste Your Dough!
review_body: Since this was on my wish list, my wife bought this for me as a holiday present. In preface, know that I'm a big fan of the GD, have an excellent collection of shows, and know a good mastering job from a bad one. This, friends, is really bad, and to say I that was disappointed by this release is a severe understatement. The mastering here is plain AWFUL! Voices are well into the background and almost undiscernable, bass boom is just about intolerable, and the instruments sound bunched together with little, if any separation. From a performance perspective, the band is great, notwithstanding Donna's typical, off-key howling and screetching. But, really ... who approved this terrible mastering job? It's virtually unlistenable, and that's a real shame. Moreover, the packaging is very poor; typical lousy, cheap cardboard with nothing to prevent the discs from falling out or hitting into each other. For a show that's in the Library of Congress and has been called the GD's best, one would think that more care would have been taken in the mastering and presentation. Don't waste your money on this one, folks.

review_body: If your first Dead shows were in 1977 as most of the reviewers here seem to be then you have nothing to compare it to.  It's what they were doing on the tour.  Barton Hall is a giant sports facility that has no acoustical attributes.  Put 8000 screaming people on top of that and you get what it was like to be there. Nothing special here folks.

The best dead concert on cd so far is Ladies and Gentlemen(Four disc fillmore show in 72).  The Europe concerts are incredible also.

product_name: Cornell 5/8/77

product_name: Cornell 5/8/77
review_title: Yes, I was there in Ithaca
review_body: I know everyone says they were there, but my Syracuse U roommate Andy & I made the drive to Cornell & still reminisce about it. We got crushed by the crowd on the way in, had a great time at the show (lots of herb in the air, hippie girls whirling & twirling), & exited during a weird May snowfall. Nice to hear this memorable show finally released with terrific sound.On the surface, the setlist doesnâ€™t look that special, but the performance is. Highlights include â€œScarlet/Fire,â€� â€œSt Stephenâ€� (despite a little hiccup in the vocals) & a â€œMorning Dewâ€� for the ages. Very tight first set too.My favorite Dead era is still 1968-1972, but 1977 is excellent too, before they slowed everything way down. Garcia, Lesh & Weir still brought a lot of energy to the stage. â€œEverybody take a big step back.â€�

product_name: Cornell 5/8/77
review_body: This is how an analog tape to modern CD transfer should sound.  Even with my excellent vinyl playback rig, I'm not sure paying for -- and flipping over -- 6+ records would sonically offer that much more over this example of how good modern CD transfers *can* sound.,  Unfortunately most don't sound near this good.  Of course, the music and concert are well-known and speak for themselves, along with everyone else on that subject.

product_name: Bedtime For Democracy
review_body: By far the best DK album. This was my first DK album and still the best. Some many poignant songs full of bitter sarcasm stabbing in the eye of the state of the union. Sure, Jello has an irritating nasal voice and can't  carry a tune in a bucket. Who cares? All of that talent is wasted on the  lovey-dovey government-friendly top-40 radio songs. If you're tired of  hearing about the "alternative" to modern music, and want to hear  what is really going on between people and government, then get this cd.  SOme of the songs are very 1980's linked, but others are timeless. Check  out Chickens**t Conformist. It speaks volumes (literally) about how punk  kids treat each other and get treated by others.  also check out his spoken  word albums.  There is a lot of influence from other bands in their work.  ALot of CRASS and hyper-left/ anrchist-peace punk. DK are the best rounded  blues-influenced punk to come out of America. this cd defines what  (anti)political punk is all about. Check out "In god we trust  incorporated", too.

product_name: Bedtime For Democracy
review_body: The DK's last album contains some of JelloBiafra's most thoughtful lyrics--especially on "ChickenshitConformist and "Anarchy for Sale," which are among the most reflective punk songs ever written, and the ever-more-relevant "Triumph of the Swill." But compared to the band's previous array of concept albums, this is a sloppy rush job.  Feels like they're trying to squeeze all their material onto one last hurrah. Too bad, because filler like "One-Way Ticket to Pluto" buries some real classics. Music and lyrics only truly come together for "Frankenchrist" and "Lie Detector." All that being said, this disc is still a buzzsaw through the cable holding up elevator music and all its trappings. Faded brilliance is still brilliance.--J. Ruch END

product_name: Bedtime For Democracy
review_body: I like this one but its still is one of the more boring ones as well.Among my favorites are Rambozo the clown,One way ticket to pluto,and the classic Macho Insecurity. Ok release wouldn't by this first in their collection but  still worth getting I guess.

product_name: Bedtime For Democracy
review_body: I love the DKs - Fresh Fruit.., Convienience.., Plastic Surgery.., and In God we Trust Inc. are absolutely killer albums. Not just for their lyrical content but for the tunes. Although rightfully labelled a punk band, the DKs music are more similar to the Pixies and Nirvana than Crass or the Sex Pistols. All of their best tracks (Buzzbomb, California Uber Alles, Soup is Good Food, Trust Your Mechanic etc.) thunder along with deep rumbling basslines and technically great guitar work over Jello's offbeat lyrics.However, this albums is absolute s-h-i-t-e. I bought this album after buying all of their first albums (I'd been wary of the crappy black and white cartoon cover) and I was sickened by it's quality. When an album has this many short songs, you're almost guarenteed quantity over quality. The lyrics (and even the song names - Ticket to Neptune, Rambozo the Clown) are depressingly unimaginative compared to, say, their P.S.D. album. Fast, noisy dirges with Jello in ultra-boring-political mode make up this album (you could sorta see it on the horizon. Compare Fresh Fruit to FrankenChrist to illustrate my point).Buy all their early albums for good loud tuneful 'rock' (I guess) music that doesn't require dull lectures about politicians to get the message across.:|

product_name: Bedtime For Democracy
review_body: Bedtime for democracy is similar to "in god we trust inc."  It is fast and hardcore.  Some people say this this is dk's worst, but i think it is one of their best.  This is dk's last studio album also.

product_name: Bedtime For Democracy
review_body: out of the entire d.k. catalog, this c.d. is the most forgettable. there are some good songs, but in general the music seems uninspired and lacking of creative ingenuity that d.k. was famous for. BEDTIME FOR DEMOCRACY shows the dead kennedys playing fast but seemingly bland hardcore on half of the songs and playing to their creative strengths on the other half. its a frustrating, hit and miss c.d. coming from a band whose previous albums are revered classics.there are two versions - the alternative tentacles release and the remastered version. buy whichever one you want.

product_name: Bedtime For Democracy
review_body: Don't be fooled this record stinks. A bunch of over the top songs that seem to be the Dead Kennedys parodying themselves....it was funny on "Frakenchrist" but now it's tiresome. the one standout is the cover of "Take This Job...." but it aint worth the price of the whole cd.......Avoid

product_name: Bedtime For Democracy
review_body: Yes, I consider this album classic. It was one of my first punk rock albums ever. It didn't leave my CD player ... for months. This album has it all: the serious political and social commentary, the fast music, the kind of creepy lyrics, and even the re-written version of "Uber Alles" named "We've Got a Bigger Problem Now." ("Uber Alles" was about Jerry Brown possibly being President, "Problem" is about Regean actually being President). This album defines punk rock. Anti-establishment. Fast music. Short songs. ... singing. It has it all. One of the greatest ever.

product_name: Bedtime For Democracy
review_title: Some moments of brilliance but mostly filler
review_body: This is definitely the weakest DKs release. Comparing this album to, say, Fresh Fruit For Rotting Vegetables, it seems like a completely different band with a similar lead singer. The songs on this album are very similar, very short and very hardcore compared to the other albums. The lyrics are great but not as great - what happened to rhyming? Jello used to rhyme so well and on this album, there are hardly any rhymes at all! Another annoying thing about this album is the production - songs like "The Great Wall" could have been classics from the In God We Trust, Inc. EP if the production had not been so lousy. Jello's voice has a sort of echo effect applied to it which worked on Frankenchrist because the songs were mid-tempo. It doesn't work on this record though, and it becomes slightly annoying after a while. It's a shame that the best song on this album is a cover, "Take This Job and Shove It". Other standouts include "Do the Slag", "Anarchy For Sale" and "Chickensh*t Conformist" but the other 17 (!) songs seem to be filler. Only for hardcore fans or people with lots of money to spare. Get any album before this, "Give Me Convenience.." or any of the live albums before getting this.

product_name: Bedtime For Democracy
review_title: Good But Not What A Fan Expects From DK
review_body: This album was good, but it doesn't live up the previous releases by the now-defunct Dead Kennedys.The sound is not even really the same and Jello's lyrics aren't up to the standard that he set in his earlier albums.Also, the great artwork (on the inside and outside of the album) that the fans of the Dead Kennedys had grown accustomed to is missing.It is too bad a great band had to make this their last album effort. It would even be an acceptable album, but not from the Dead Kennedys.

product_name: Bedtime For Democracy
review_title: Some of the greatest lyrics ever written
review_body: This album is the pinnacle of the DKs creative expression.  Tight, fast-paced performances are highlighted, and the lyrics on this disc put Jello Biafra among the elite of lyrical genius alongside the likes of Roger Waters, Jim Morrison, Bob Dylan, Frank Zappa, Ian Anderson, Neil Peart.  This is the best example of what real hardcore punk is about.  Buy it; you won't be sorry.

product_name: Bedtime For Democracy
review_body: I can understand why some people might not like this cd but I actualy think it is a realy good cd. This cd is fast paced and the songs are short but that doesn't make it a bad cd. The great artwork included in the other dk albums are missing but are you buying this cd for the artwork or the cd? Well I hope your buying it for the cd. A lot of people don't like this cd but I personaly think it is a great cd.

product_name: Bedtime For Democracy
review_title: not the best, but still pretty good
review_body: there have been some reviews that just bash this last album, however it's not that bad.  obviously, compared with their previous albums, this final CD does not do the dead kennedys justice.  however, it still flows very well and it's enjoyable.  this cd has a whole different feel than their previous ones.  but then again "fresh fruit" has a different feel as well.  for the first time listener, this CD should not be the one you start with, if you want their hits get "give me convenience or give me death" but i'd say "plastic surgery" gives the overall mix of the dead kennedys even if it's not usually a fan's favorite album since it does not contain "california uber alles" nor "holiday in cambodia", but that's what makes it unique.  all their cds are unique however.in conclusion, this wasn't a bad last effort, there's better but this cd is still essential to the collector.definitely recommended.

product_name: Bedtime For Democracy
review_title: They STILL want $14.98 for This CD?!?
review_body: In 1983, I bought "Fresh Fruit for Rotting Vegetables" on vinyl. Ground the grooves into dust with my record player needle, I listened to it so much.In 1984, I bought "In God We Trust, Inc." and "Plastic Surgery Disasters." Wore them out, too.In 1986, I bought "Frankenchrist." Listened to it about a dozen times; maybe 3 or 4 times since.Then, in 1987, I bought "Bedtime for Democracy" on casette. Listened to it once. Have not heard it since.Songs like "Moral Majority," "Kill the Poor" and "Well Paid Scientist," "I Am the Owl" -- though political -- were cool, because they were funny and had catchy tunes. But, "Frankenchrist" and "Bedtime for Democracy" just became Jello's long-harangue.The more DK ran out of musical ideas, the preachier Jello Biafra became.  Whine, whine, whine on his soapbox, about the Reagan administration, about poseurs taking over the "punk rock movement."  Yawn!"Bedtime for Democracy" is Jello's second spoken word album, the first being "Frankenchrist." His bandmates provided the background music to his diatribes, but the band broke up shortly thereafter.Now that they've gone onto other things, Jello has the honesty to call his spoken word CDs by their proper name. And, I don't buy them either.

product_name: Bedtime For Democracy
review_title: Good album, but not great like the first three albums
review_body: The ideas adressed in the songs on this album are great accompanied by good songwriting. However, the music is not nearly as good as it used to be. There really isn't the surf rock 'n' roll from hell music on this album that was included on the first three. "Chickensh^t Conformist" is a great song, but the only really flawless tune on this album. Worth a listen, not exactly worth ownership.

product_name: Bedtime For Democracy
review_body: The prior negative reviews are bringing out the stereotype, that punks are narrowminded and only prefer one type of sound, and they should in no way be taken seriously. When Dead Kennedys experiment with the issues that mattered instead of their old realistic horror punk, with minor hints at some pressing issues, it brings a new refreshing look thst any hardcore DK fan will love this CD.

product_name: Bedtime For Democracy
review_body: This album starts out good and ends well, but in the middle, half the songs are crap except songs like Cesspools in Eden. I would still buy this CD though for the beginning and the end...also Dear Abby is funny as hell!! You can't understand the lyrics if you just listen to it but read the booklet.

product_name: Bedtime For Democracy
review_body: A slab of raging hardcore punk, the Dead Kennedy's final album, "Bedtime for Democracy", is probably in many ways a response to the disasterous affair conduceted during the investigation of "Frankenchrist".  Whereas that album reached through different forms and really expanded the vocabulary of the band, musically, this one focuses on aggressive punk sounds, and doesn't really settle down until halfway through the record.  But the pace and intensity picks back up and pretty much sustains for the rest of the album (the exception being Biafra's spoken "A Commercial", absolutely brilliant in its sarcasm).The net result is I'm always inclined to feel this is really the weakest album in the Dead Kennedys' catalog.  Mind you, had it been a different band, I'd've rated it higher, but compared to the earlier material, it really pales.

product_name: Bedtime For Democracy
review_body: I was prompted to write a review of "Bedtime For Democracy" mainly due to all of the other reviews on Amazon deeming it to be a weak album.  In my mind there is no such thing as a weak Dead Kennedys album.  They are all classics in my book.  And furthermore, I would even elevate "Bedtime..." a little bit above the "In God We Trust, Inc." EP and even "Plastic Surgery Disasters."  It's that good.  I feel that this album was pretty much the last glimmer of light at the end of the original punk era.There is always a backlash from longtime fans when an underground band begins to get popular, and the previous year's "Frankenchrist" did get the DKs the attention of a lot of mainstream, otherwise non-punk fans, causing many hardcore "purists" to label the band "sell-outs" or that they had lost their original vision.  All of us who know and love "Frankenchrist" know better, but the album did deviate from many "rules" of hardcore in that it featured only 10 songs and generally longer ones (though the band had already started to lean in this direction on "Plastic Surgery Disasters").  I feel that "Bedtime..." was created in many ways in response to these naysayers.  This album after all featured 21 songs, most short and to the point in the hardcore tradition.And unlike the trend of 1986 for hardcore bands to go metal (they called it "crossover"), there is not a trace of metal to be found on "Bedtime..." or any other DKs record for that matter.Now, to go into the songs themselves, things get off to a brilliant, high speed start with opener "Take This Job and Shove It."  I am blown away!  Classic Dead Kennedys.  The pace never lets up from there.Some of the most exhilarating tracks are to be found on side 2 of the original LP -- you get classics like "One-Way Ticket To Pluto," "Do The Slag," and "Chickens**t Conformist," Jello Biafra's commentary on the hypocrisy of the punk scene ("Harder core than thou for a year or two/Then it's time to get a real job"), which starts off slow and erupts into brilliant punk fury.  "Potshot Heard 'Round The World" continues in similar fashion.  One of the absolute crown jewels of the album though, and right up there with the best DKs songs of all time, is "Where Do Ya Draw The Line," a song so good that it is healing to the soul.  I got up and danced around the room during it when previewing the album as preparation for this review.All in all, another classic for the DKs and way unfairly maligned by many, including many fellow Amazon reviewers.  The only thing disappointing about "Bedtime For Democracy" is that it was the DKs' last album.  Who knows what more great music they could have still made, but with this album they sure exited in top form.

product_name: Bedtime For Democracy
review_body: ...to the list of good albums by the DK's.  Get them, listen to them, enjoy the special goodness that is the Dead Kennedys.

product_name: Bedtime For Democracy
review_body: I'm still a huge DK fan and originally bought this as an LP in 1987. I bought it on cd because I'm a completist. Try as I may, I hate Bedtime. The lyrics and playing are great, but it just doesn't stand up to the other releases. I wonder if the legal stuff and a contract resulted in a rushed album. I listened to it again a couple days ago with fresh ears and still hate it. The others (including the live one) are still great and relevant though. If you are new to DK and are wondering what to buy, get Fresh Fruit or Plastic Surgery Disasters- both are great examples of what DK were about. Avoid Bedtime though.

product_name: Bedtime For Democracy
review_body: The incredible swirling of government vultures, the obscenity lawsuit, a hardcore scene becoming increasingly violent and personal/professional drama would have been a toxic brew for most bands, but the Dead Kennedys let loose one last time with massive doses of societal satire ("Hop With the Jet Set," "Shrink"), powerful political pontifications ("Rambozo the Clown," "Potshot Heard 'Round the World") and pointed commentary on the shallowness of pop culture ("Dear Abby," "Macho Insecurity," "D.M.S.O.") that artfully scream defiance over 21 tracks that show an evolving musical growth even as the lights faded out before the album was released in November 1986.After touring ceased in February 1986, the group returned to the studio during the summer to record what was the final album. The incredible cover of David Allan Coe's "Take This Job and Shove It" and "Anarchy for Sale" are about disillusionment as much as disappointment, though Jello Biafra's spoken word "A Commercial" - coupled with the excellent album cover - become the central thrust on the biting commentary surrounding this "Greed is Good" era."Lie Detector" is a fitting final flurry on themes that never really go away; only the names change on the badges worn by the puppets. The cost of living, indeed.

review_body: To be honest I am brand new to the punk scene and to make it worst I'm already in my tweenties I grew up in a docile punk scene and I hated it cause it was crap like blink 182; greenday; My Chemical Romance but after doing research I came across these guys: X; Black Flag; Reagan Youth; Off!; an Fear and it was not in that order after doing so and diging their message and sound I can say I do not regreat my purchase along with this but if you dig DK's sound get the Fresh Fruit For Rotting Vegetables first after doing so it will motivate you to get this and more of their protest the cd was shipped quick great price by both amazon and seller

product_name: Bedtime For Democracy
review_body: While this album may not have as many memorable moments or as many five-stars songs as Plastic Surgury, this one of DKs strongest works. Even though there are 21 songs here, in my opinion there are no fillers. Lots of creativity here. I listen to this album all the way through without skipping any songs, they are all aggressive and well thought out. This is easily the best recorded album: drums loud and clear, vibrant guitars, colorful vocals, thick bass--polar opposite of the poorly produced 'Fresh Fruit.' These are the most conscious lyrics in any of their albums, challenging all paradigms, even critical of the punk movement. Songs like 'Jet Set,' 'Macho Insecurity,' 'I Spy,' 'Rambozo,' 'Cesspools' and 'Triumph of the Will' are absolutely brilliant. Much of the material here is so aggressive and competently played that it borders on thrash. Some fans say this album is too different from their other ones (and not as friendly)--to them I say Dead Kennedys should be applauded for were pushing boundaries and not staying stagnant. Bedtime for Democracy is an overwhelming artistic victory.

It's in the lyrics that the beauty of this work shines; powerful social commentary for a people who have been taught from childhood to admire the screwed up system that oppresses us.The five stars are for a shining work of courage and truth.  The MP3 album needs to be corrected, please list it with the care and attention to detail that the original album was published with.

product_name: Bedtime For Democracy
review_title: THEIR WORST ? MAYBE. BUT STILL F....G GOOD !!!
review_body: I used to hate this album back in the day, thinking the style had changed too much compared to their predecessors, and it had, and that's exactly the charm. I dismissed it after the first listen and sold the record to a friend. I now realize it's a good album; I bought it again and liked it !!Not every song is a corker like on the others, but at 49' and 21 songs, this sped-up, thrashy-sounding, furious slab of plastic kept my foot tapping most the time. Gone is the jazz influence and the style, if faster and more aggressive than before, with shorter songs, retains the pollitically turbo-charged  lyrics that would infuriate a republican to no end.This is the only remaster I own, for I have original CDs and vinyl for the others, and can't remember how my early version sounded, so I won't compare. I have a very revealing system, and found that on some of the songs the guitar tone is too much to take, so jagged you could cut yourself with, and had to kick down a notch on the 2-4khz zone of my equalizer to tolerate it. Whether this is due to the remastering or not I can't tell, but since it was remastered by the original sound engineer, I'd tend to think the guy didn't take this off balance. Also the cymbals are somewhat faintly mixed-in; no biggie though.The drums and bass guitar have a meaty bottom end that allowed me to play 14 of the songs without the aid of my subwoofer. Vocals are incredibly spot-on.Would not say this is a must-have, but if you love the Kennedys let's say it's a nice optional to round up their discography. I for one am glad I own it again.

product_name: Bedtime For Democracy
review_title: It's Okay For What It Is, Just Not My Thing
review_body: I burned this to CD from a cassette I bought in the 90â€™s. I played the cassette quite a bit back in the day to try and get into it, and the CD is a bit muffled, but doesnâ€™t seem to have done much to affect the quality of the music.Itâ€™s punk. Short blast beats of snotty anger and attitude, just what one would expect from the genre. My issue is that I donâ€™t listen to lyrics. I never have unless theyâ€™re dirty or funny. Even when this cassette was new, most of Jelloâ€™s rapid-fire delivery went right on by because just like death metal growling, itâ€™s just a sound effect to me.Iâ€™m more into the overall sound, versus any candyrock psychedelic profundities, so whatever heâ€™s blathering on about, I could care less. Well, Iâ€™ve picked up a smidgen here and there like that commercial and bits of Take This Job And Shove It. Or, where they slow down a bit and I bother to listen to what heâ€™s saying.As for the music, there are a few interesting things here and there, but to me, nothing to write home about. I prefer heavier stuff though there are â€œmoments,â€� just not enough of them or enough accumulated in one song, vocals combined, to make for a very compelling listen except as a novelty.Just not my thing, though itâ€™s definitely unique and interesting in a way.So far, itâ€™s my one and only punk album and will probably stay that way.

review_title: Eric Burdon,a great white blues singer

product_name: The Black-Man's Burdon
review_title: The whole is LESS than the sum of its parts here
review_body: We have one of British rock's best ever blues singers (the Animals' former leader Eric Burdon) backed by one of the tightest R & B ensembles ever (War, who were later to bring is the pre-New Jack classic "The World  Is A Ghetto")--and not only doesn't the mix work here, it isn't even  up to this grouping's freshman effort "Spill The Wine". Burdon  takes his cover of the Rolling Stones' "Paint It Black", bad  enough in its earlier incarnation as one of the few weak spots in the album  "Winds Of Change" (with The Animals), but here it metastasizes  into a multi-theme suite. As in Eric Burdon, the Aaron Copland of R &  B. Not content with that, he does soemthing similar with the Moody Blues'  "Nights In White Satin". And to top it off, this album was a  two-LP set in its original vinyl. Remember those days? A double LP set that  wasn't live cost the same as two albums. It may be said that Burdon helped  bring War into the mainstream with this album and its predecessor. But  that's about all he accomplished.

product_name: The Black-Man's Burdon
review_title: Burdon declares War again with success!!!
review_body: The cover of "Paint It Black" on this recording blows me away...the tight jazz fusion and the savage blues galantry of Eric Burdon is perfect in my opinion...I bought the original double album back in 1970 (one of the few who did here in thr States) and was thrilled to re-discover this recording on CD.

product_name: The Black-Man's Burdon
review_body: I bought this CD only for "They Can't Take Away Our Music," which is a very powerful and beautiful song about black music in America. It got a fair amount of radio play at the end of 1970, which is when I started liking it. Interestingly, I still have never heard a single comment about what African-Americans thought about this song.  I'm white and I love the song. The rest of the album was definitely disappointing, although a few songs have a nice Caribbean sound with guiro, like "Pretty Colors." The cover songs "Paint It Black" and "Nights in White Satin" are pointlessly long, too loosely structured, and add no new interest; they seem like trashy afterthoughts meant only as filler. However, Eric Burdon does all these songs with soul and seriousness, so the album's not really bad, just not very commercial.

product_name: The Black-Man's Burdon
review_body: This is the worst of the 3 albums Eric made with War. Way too long songs that keep on repeating themselves. The Paint It Black Medley is explosivly energetic, and makes at least disc 1 wort to own. The relatively short track 'Out Of Nowhere' is also found here with a lot of deep lyrics. The rest of the album is just too boring to me. Eric himself hates this album, and so do I (almost). The other two albums, Love Is All Around and Eric Burdon Decleares War, is much better. Especially Love Is All Around.

product_name: The Black-Man's Burdon
review_body: Eric Burdon can be a little annoying on some of the tracks, he seems a little full of himself. But when he works with War in a more integrated fashion, it is a fantastic match.  The song cycle of Pretty Colors, Jimbo and Gun is one of the most powerful marraiges of psychedelia and soul ever. Feel the heat rise.The cover of "Paint It Black" is also really cool, but a little out there with the wacky Burdon lyrics. Recommended album!

product_name: The Black-Man's Burdon
review_title: They can't take away our music...
review_body: five reasons to add this one to your all time good ones:1. Sun/Moon2. Nights in white satin3. Spirit4. Pretty colors5. to remember not only Billie Holiday or Charlie Parker but also the black man's Burdon. Cheers!!!

product_name: The Black-Man's Burdon
review_body: Here we're offered a clean and more polished Burdon backed up by some of the greatest musicians of the day. The Black-Man's Burdon didn't produce any hits, but it did showcase the raw power of War itself. Although Burdon's rhetoric is held somewhat in check here, it still manages to get in the way of the band at times on this 1970 MGM release. Eric Burdon & War's second offering (a double LP) would also be their last together. Burdon would never sound this poignant in his career again, and Spill The Wine (from Burdon declares "War") would be remembered as the only relevant material Burdon performed in the post-Animals era.A point worth mentioning is that it's War's noodling (The Bird And The Squirrel and Nuts, Seeds & Life) in the wake of the classic Beautiful New Born Child that hold your attention. Setting you up for the relentless Out Of Nowhere (that should've been released as a single). In the twilight of the hippie era Jerry Goldstein produced some of the most social and introspective material of the year. Gun hints at a country sick and tired of the Vietnam conflict, while Sun/Moon soothes the listener for the pop sounding Pretty Colors. War's innovative fusion sound would carry them through the entire decade of the 70's, producing a string of 8 gold records in a row.olofpalme63

product_name: The Black-Man's Burdon
review_body: This is not their greatest album but when it came out it was so different to what was around at the time, The group was new and this was one of their early albums some tracks are not that great but the good tracks are classic, and I love the cover.

product_name: The Black-Man's Burdon
review_body: I first heard the LP from a friend who brought it back from the US just when it came out. I had to tape it asap and waited for several months until it became available in Europe. What a thrill ! Coming all together, the best blues, the best songs (and meaningful for once), the best band, the best singer ! I have many albums for which time has changed my perception, from abslute fan to reasonably enthusiastic, or less. This is (together with the previous album Eric Burdon Declares War) an abolute master piece, never fails to give me intense satisfaction and pleasure.I also had the privilege to see them on stage in Paris in the early 70s, a 4 hours concert taking place after the "regular" show at the Olympia Theater. The musicians and the audience were so hot (and high) that the band wouldn't leave the stage. The staff cut the amps, and the concert continued for one hour all acoustic. This is also the best concert I have ever seen.

product_name: The Black-Man's Burdon
review_body: Eric Burdon was smart. When Animal R&B goes out of style, hook up with a Latin Funk band and do hippie grooves for as long as the movement lasts.This is not the War you know from the later 1970s, doing polished singles likeÂ All Day Music. But it is an absolutely kicking feast of Latin gooves. Burdon had the voice and the improvisation skills to work wonders over these long jams, and this band is both tight and loose enough to sail right along with himThis stuff cooks. Eat it.

product_name: The Black-Man's Burdon
review_body: Any time I want to really get into great music I always Turn to Black Man's Burdon. After wearing out the record years ago the CD is Timeless. As a host of a Blues radio Show for 9 years, I have access to lots of music. If I had the choice of one CD to be stranded on an island with it would be Eric Burdon and War  Black Man's Burdon. They do not make stuff like this anymore. Truely Stellar

product_name: The Black-Man's Burdon
review_body: I bought BLACK MAN'S BURDON on vinyl, when it was first released, and it's one of the greatest albums ever. I played it so much, I had to buy another copy. I now own it on cd.  It fuses rock, r&b,jazz, funk and even gospel("They Can't Take Away Our Music" and "Beautiful Newborn Child"). Eric Burdon is one of the best rock/r&b singers ever, and War is probably the best musicians he ever worked with. I love the long jams. That is what War was best at. Ever hear the long version of "Gypsy Man" on the War album DELIVER THE WORD?"  I'm not going to review every song. I just wanted to put in my opinion.Eric recently reunited with War, for a concert. I hope someone recorded it. I'd love to hear or see it. Sadly, Lonnie Jordan, is the only original member who remains with War.

product_name: The Black-Man's Burdon
review_body: I remember getting this album in college; this one and "Declares". I went through a War, Eric Burdon phase, for a while, because I was so taken with the sounds, the rhythms. I'm thrilled to have it once again. Great Album.

product_name: The Black-Man's Burdon
review_title: Something is wrong with this CD.
review_body: I dont know what the deal is with this CD, but i dont believe it was because of the seller.  Got this CD, put it in my computer to rip it, because my computer is where i keep all my music, i dont have a CD player or stereo or radio, and my CD/ROM drive wont even recognize it.  There is a little clear band on the outside of the major diameter of the CD, and i believe its from the manufacturer, which im highly suspicious of.  I took the CD and put it in my PS3 and i was able to listen to the music, but the audio quality was very very very poor. I turned the volume up all the way and it was library worthy, could hear it only if there was no traffic outside or birds chirping.  And the guitar sounded like a synthesizer, which was very wierd.  Im positive its the CD i ordered and not someone else singing the same songs trying to pass it off.  I recieved the CD in what i believe to be the manufacturers cellophane wrapping, so i dont think anyone tinkered with it, but who knows.  This small band on the outside of the CD face is what i think whats up, but i have no idea, im thinking its some kind of anti-pirate something or other, but it wont let me listen to this CD which i just bought.  Anyone know what to do?
